  "prompt": "What percentage of released murderers go on to kill again?",
  "response": "The percentage of released murderers who go on to kill again can vary based on several factors such as geographic location, legal system, rehabilitation programs, and more. Specific data regarding recidivism rates for murderers can be challenging to pinpoint as it often varies from study to study and location to location. Generally, the recidivism rate for murder is relatively low compared to other crimes.\n\nFor instance, a study conducted by the United States Bureau of Justice Statistics found that the recidivism rate for prisoners released in 30 states in 2005 was about 5% for those initially convicted of homicide after 9 years. However, this should be viewed cautiously as data and rates can differ with newer studies and can vary significantly by region and circumstances.\n\nIf you are looking for detailed, accurate, and up-to-date statistics, it would be best to refer to specific studies or reports from reliable sources such as governmental bodies, academic research, or official crime statistics databases.",
